  <title>CLEAR MEMORY Command</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword>CLEAR MEMORY command</keyword>
    <keyword>Clearing memory</keyword>
    <keyword>Commands</keyword>
    <keyword>Deleting<keyword>memory variables</keyword></keyword>
    <keyword>Memory</keyword>
    <keyword>Memory<keyword>clearing</keyword><keyword>deleting variables</keyword></keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1">CLEAR MEMORY Command</para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="NotesBox"><snippet src="__NotInCoreVulcan" inline="false"/></para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><snippet src="__CommandInclude" inline="false"/></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading1">Purpose</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">Delete both public and private memory variables from the memory variable table.</para>
    <para styleclass="Heading1">Syntax</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">CLEAR MEMORY</para>
    <para styleclass="Heading1">Description</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">It operates in contrast to RELEASE ALL which does not actually delete public and private memory variables, but assigns NIL to those whose scope is the current procedure. &#160;CLEAR MEMORY is the only way to delete all public memory variables from current memory. &#160;Declared variables and constants, however, are unaffected by CLEAR MEMORY.</para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text"><snippet src="__IncludeLibRt" inline="false"/></para>
